## Session 2: Kafka Producers in Depth


```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Application] -->|send| S[Serializer]
    S --> P[Partitioner]
    P --> B[Record Batch]
    B -->|linger.ms / batch.size| N[Network Thread]
    N -->|acks=0,1,all| BR[Broker]
    BR -->|success| CB[Callback]
    BR -->|failure| R[Retry Queue]
    R -->|retries| N
```


The Kafka producer is far more than a simple send() call. Understanding its internal pipeline — from serialization through batching, network I/O, acknowledgment, and retry — is essential for building reliable, high-throughput systems and for answering advanced interview questions.

### Producer Internals

When you call `producer.send(record)`, Kafka does not immediately write to the network. Instead:
1. **Serialize** key and value using configured serializers
2. **Determine partition** via key hash, round-robin, or custom Partitioner
3. **Add to RecordAccumulator** — an in-memory buffer organized by (topic, partition)
4. **Batch sender thread** drains the accumulator and sends batches to brokers
5. **Await acknowledgment** from the broker(s) per acks config
6. **Callback** is invoked with metadata (offset, partition, timestamp) or exception

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;
import java.util.Properties;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;

public class DurableProducer {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());

        // Durability settings
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.RETRIES_CONFIG, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, true);

        // Throughput settings
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BATCH_SIZE_CONFIG, 32768);        // 32 KB
        props.put(ProducerConfig.LINGER_MS_CONFIG, 10);            // wait 10ms
        props.put(ProducerConfig.COMPRESSION_TYPE_CONFIG, "snappy");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BUFFER_MEMORY_CONFIG, 67108864L); // 64 MB

        try (KafkaProducer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props)) {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
                String key   = "user-" + (i % 100);  // 100 distinct users
                String value = "{\"event\":\"page_view\",\"userId\":\"" + key + "\"}";

                ProducerRecord<String, String> record =
                    new ProducerRecord<>("page-views", key, value);

                // Async send with callback
                producer.send(record, (metadata, exception) -> {
                    if (exception != null) {
                        System.err.println("Send failed: " + exception.getMessage());
                    } else {
                        System.out.printf("Sent to partition=%d offset=%d%n",
                            metadata.partition(), metadata.offset());
                    }
                });
            }
            producer.flush(); // ensure all buffered records are sent
        }
    }
}
```

### Acks — Durability Trade-offs

- **acks=0**: Producer fires and forgets. No wait for broker response. Maximum throughput, zero durability. Use only for metrics or logs where loss is acceptable.
- **acks=1**: Leader acknowledges after writing to its local log. Follower replication is async. If the leader crashes before replication, data is lost. Moderate throughput.
- **acks=all** (or -1): All ISR members must acknowledge. Combined with `min.insync.replicas=2`, this guarantees at least 2 replicas hold the data before acknowledgment. Lowest throughput, highest durability.

### Idempotent Producer

With `enable.idempotence=true`, each producer instance receives a **Producer ID (PID)** from the broker. Every batch is tagged with a monotonically increasing **sequence number** per partition. If the producer retries a failed send, the broker compares the incoming sequence number against what it last wrote and silently discards duplicates — exactly-once at the producer level within a session.

### Batching and Linger

`batch.size` (default 16 KB) controls the maximum size of a batch per partition. `linger.ms` (default 0) adds a deliberate delay to allow more records to accumulate. Setting `linger.ms=10` can increase batch fill rate dramatically, boosting throughput at the cost of a small latency increase.

### Compression

Compression is applied per batch: `snappy` (low CPU, good ratio), `lz4` (fastest), `gzip` (best ratio, highest CPU), `zstd` (best ratio + speed balance, Kafka 2.1+). Compressed batches are written to disk and decompressed by the consumer — not by the broker — making this effectively free from the broker's perspective.

### Custom Partitioner

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.Partitioner;
import org.apache.kafka.common.Cluster;
import java.util.Map;

public class RegionPartitioner implements Partitioner {
    @Override
    public int partition(String topic, Object key, byte[] keyBytes,
                         Object value, byte[] valueBytes, Cluster cluster) {
        int numPartitions = cluster.partitionsForTopic(topic).size();
        if (key != null && key.toString().startsWith("EU-")) {
            // Pin EU traffic to the first half of partitions
            return Math.abs(key.hashCode()) % (numPartitions / 2);
        }
        return Math.abs(key.hashCode()) % numPartitions;
    }
    @Override public void close() {}
    @Override public void configure(Map<String, ?> configs) {}
}
```

### Interview Insight

"What's the difference between `retries` and idempotence?" — Retries alone can cause duplicates if the original write succeeded but the ack was lost. Idempotence makes retries safe by using sequence numbers to deduplicate. Always use both together in production.

## Session 3: Consumers and Consumer Groups


```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph Consumer Group A
        C1[Consumer 1]
        C2[Consumer 2]
    end
    subgraph Topic: events
        P0[Partition 0]
        P1[Partition 1]
        P2[Partition 2]
    end
    P0 -->|assigned| C1
    P1 -->|assigned| C1
    P2 -->|assigned| C2
    GC[Group Coordinator<br/>Broker] -.->|rebalance| C1
    GC -.->|rebalance| C2
```


Kafka's consumer model is pull-based: consumers call `poll()` on their own schedule, at their own rate. This decouples consumer speed from producer speed and allows consumers to process at whatever pace their application requires. Mastering the consumer group protocol, offset management, and the poll loop is essential for building reliable consumers.

### Consumer Group Protocol

All consumers with the same `group.id` form a **consumer group**. Kafka's **Group Coordinator** (a designated broker) manages group membership. When a group starts, the coordinator facilitates the **JoinGroup** / **SyncGroup** handshake: one consumer is elected the **Group Leader**, computes the partition assignment using a configured **Assignor**, and sends the assignment back through the coordinator.

**Assignors:**
- `RangeAssignor` (default): partitions assigned in ranges per topic. Can be uneven.
- `RoundRobinAssignor`: round-robin across all partitions of all topics. More even.
- `StickyAssignor`: minimizes partition movement between rebalances.
- `CooperativeStickyAssignor`: incremental rebalance — only revoked partitions pause, others keep consuming. Eliminates the stop-the-world rebalance.

### The Poll Loop

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.TopicPartition;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer;
import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.*;

public class RobustConsumer {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "order-processor-v1");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringDeserializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringDeserializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, false);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.AUTO_OFFSET_RESET_CONFIG, "earliest");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.MAX_POLL_RECORDS_CONFIG, 250);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.SESSION_TIMEOUT_MS_CONFIG, 45000);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.HEARTBEAT_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG, 3000);

        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);

        consumer.subscribe(Collections.singletonList("orders"),
            new ConsumerRebalanceListener() {
                @Override
                public void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
                    // Commit offsets before losing partition ownership
                    System.out.println("Partitions revoked: " + partitions);
                    consumer.commitSync();
                }
                @Override
                public void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
                    System.out.println("Partitions assigned: " + partitions);
                }
            });

        try {
            while (true) {
                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                    consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(500));

                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    System.out.printf("partition=%d offset=%d key=%s value=%s%n",
                        record.partition(), record.offset(),
                        record.key(), record.value());
                    processOrder(record.value());
                }

                // Manual sync commit after processing the batch
                if (!records.isEmpty()) {
                    consumer.commitSync();
                }
            }
        } finally {
            consumer.close(); // triggers graceful rebalance
        }
    }

    static void processOrder(String orderJson) {
        // Business logic here
    }
}
```

### Offset Commit Strategies

**Auto-commit** (`enable.auto.commit=true`): Kafka commits the last polled offset every `auto.commit.interval.ms` (default 5 s). Risk: if the consumer crashes between the auto-commit and finishing processing, those messages are skipped (at-most-once).

**Manual sync commit** (`commitSync()`): Blocks until the broker confirms the commit. Guarantees at-least-once — if processing succeeds, commit succeeds. If the consumer crashes before committing, messages are reprocessed on restart.

**Manual async commit** (`commitAsync(callback)`): Does not block. Higher throughput. Risk: if async commit fails, a later successful commit may cover it, but order of commits is not guaranteed across retries. Best pattern: use async during normal operation, fall back to sync on shutdown.

**Per-partition commit** (`commitSync(offsetMap)`): Commit offsets at specific positions per partition — useful when processing results are written to an external store and you want offset commits to be transactionally aligned.

### Heartbeat and Session Timeout

Consumers send heartbeats to the Group Coordinator on a background thread every `heartbeat.interval.ms` (default 3 s). If the coordinator does not hear from a consumer within `session.timeout.ms` (default 45 s), it declares the consumer dead and triggers a rebalance. Separately, if the consumer does not call `poll()` within `max.poll.interval.ms` (default 5 min), it is also considered failed. This catches consumers that are alive (sending heartbeats) but stuck in slow processing.

### Interview Insight

"How do you avoid duplicate processing in a consumer?" — Enable `enable.auto.commit=false`, process the batch, then call `commitSync()`. Wrap the external side effect (e.g., database write) and the commit in an idempotent design so re-processing the same record has no net effect.

## Session 4: Partitioning and Message Ordering

```mermaid
graph TB
    P[Producer] --> T[Topic]
    T --> P0[Partition 0]
    T --> P1[Partition 1]
    T --> P2[Partition 2]
    P0 --> CG1[Consumer Group 1]
    P1 --> CG1
    P2 --> CG2[Consumer Group 2]
```


Partition selection is one of the most consequential decisions when designing a Kafka-based system. It affects ordering guarantees, load distribution, scalability, and even failure behavior. This session covers how Kafka routes messages to partitions and the trade-offs of each approach.

### How the Default Partitioner Works

Kafka's default partitioner (`DefaultPartitioner` / `UniformStickyPartitioner` in newer versions) uses the following logic:

1. **Key is null**: Records are distributed in a round-robin fashion across available partitions — optimized in newer Kafka versions to be sticky per batch (stick to one partition until the batch is full, then switch) to improve batching efficiency.
2. **Key is present**: Partition = `murmur2(keyBytes) % numPartitions`. The same key always maps to the same partition, as long as the partition count does not change.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;
import java.util.Properties;

public class PartitionKeyDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, true);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all");

        try (KafkaProducer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props)) {
            // All events for order-42 go to the same partition — ordering guaranteed
            String orderId = "order-42";
            String[] events = {"CREATED", "PAYMENT_RECEIVED", "SHIPPED", "DELIVERED"};

            for (String event : events) {
                ProducerRecord<String, String> record = new ProducerRecord<>(
                    "order-events", orderId, event);
                producer.send(record).get(); // sync for demo clarity
                System.out.println("Sent: " + event + " for key=" + orderId);
            }
        }
        // Consumer will receive CREATED -> PAYMENT_RECEIVED -> SHIPPED -> DELIVERED
        // in exactly this order for this orderId
    }
}
```

### Ordering Guarantee Scope

Kafka guarantees **total ordering within a single partition**. A consumer reading partition P will receive records in the exact order they were appended by the producer. There is no ordering guarantee across partitions.

This means:
- If order-42 events all go to partition 2, they arrive in order.
- If order-43 events go to partition 5, they also arrive in order — but relative ordering between order-42 and order-43 events is undefined.

### Hot Partition Problem

If your key space is skewed — e.g., one customer generates 80% of all events — the partition that key maps to will be overwhelmed while others sit idle.

**Mitigation strategies:**
1. **Better key choice**: Use a more evenly distributed key (e.g., `userId + sessionId`).
2. **Salting**: Append a random suffix to hot keys for writes, aggregate during reads.
3. **Repartitioning in Kafka Streams**: Use a `through()` or `repartition()` step.
4. **Monitoring**: Alert on per-partition message rate skew.

### Custom Partitioner

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.Partitioner;
import org.apache.kafka.common.Cluster;
import java.util.Map;

public class TierPartitioner implements Partitioner {
    // Reserve the last 2 partitions for premium users
    private static final int PREMIUM_PARTITIONS = 2;

    @Override
    public int partition(String topic, Object key, byte[] keyBytes,
                         Object value, byte[] valueBytes, Cluster cluster) {
        int total = cluster.partitionsForTopic(topic).size();
        int standardPartitions = total - PREMIUM_PARTITIONS;

        if (key != null && key.toString().startsWith("PREMIUM:")) {
            // Spread premium users across last N partitions
            int hash = Math.abs(key.hashCode());
            return standardPartitions + (hash % PREMIUM_PARTITIONS);
        }
        // Standard users get first (total - PREMIUM_PARTITIONS) partitions
        return Math.abs(key.hashCode()) % standardPartitions;
    }

    @Override public void close() {}
    @Override public void configure(Map<String, ?> configs) {}
}
```

Register via: `props.put(ProducerConfig.PARTITIONER_CLASS_CONFIG, TierPartitioner.class.getName())`

### Changing Partition Count

Kafka allows **increasing** partition count but never decreasing it. When partition count changes, the key-to-partition mapping changes for new messages (murmur2(key) % newCount). **This breaks ordering for existing keys** — events for the same key may land in different partitions before and after the change. Plan partition count carefully upfront based on peak throughput targets and expected consumer count.

### Interview Insight

"How do you ensure global ordering of all messages in a topic?" — Set the topic to 1 partition. This is the only way to achieve global ordering in Kafka. The trade-off is zero parallelism: only one consumer can process the topic at a time. Global ordering + high throughput are fundamentally in tension in Kafka's architecture.

## Session 5: Replication and Fault Tolerance

```mermaid
graph TB
    P[Producer] --> T[Topic]
    T --> P0[Partition 0]
    T --> P1[Partition 1]
    T --> P2[Partition 2]
    P0 --> CG1[Consumer Group 1]
    P1 --> CG1
    P2 --> CG2[Consumer Group 2]
```


Kafka's durability story rests entirely on replication. Understanding how replicas stay synchronized, what happens during broker failures, and how to configure the right trade-off between availability and durability is critical for production operations and senior-level interviews.

### Replication Architecture

Each partition has exactly one **Leader** replica and zero or more **Follower** replicas. The total number of replicas is the **replication factor (RF)**. Followers continuously fetch from the leader using the same internal protocol as consumers, appending records to their local log.

```
Partition: orders-0  (RF=3)

  Broker 1 (Leader)   ← Producers write here
  Broker 2 (Follower) ← Replicates from Broker 1
  Broker 3 (Follower) ← Replicates from Broker 1

  ISR = [1, 2, 3]   (all three are in-sync)
```

A follower is considered **in-sync** if it has fetched all messages from the leader within `replica.lag.time.max.ms` (default 30,000 ms). If a follower falls behind (due to network slowness, GC pauses, or disk I/O), it is removed from the ISR. When it catches up again, it rejoins.

### Configuring Durability

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.admin.AdminClient;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.admin.NewTopic;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.admin.AlterConfigsResult;
import org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigResource;
import org.apache.kafka.common.config.ConfigResource.Type;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;
import java.util.*;

public class DurabilityConfig {

    // Producer configured for maximum durability
    public static KafkaProducer<String, String> createDurableProducer() {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());

        // acks=all: wait for all ISR members
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all");
        // Unlimited retries with idempotence
        props.put(ProducerConfig.RETRIES_CONFIG, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, true);
        // Controlled retry delay
        props.put(ProducerConfig.RETRY_BACKOFF_MS_CONFIG, 200);
        // Bound total time waiting for a single send
        props.put(ProducerConfig.DELIVERY_TIMEOUT_MS_CONFIG, 120000);

        return new KafkaProducer<>(props);
    }

    // Topic configuration: RF=3, min.insync.replicas=2
    public static void createDurableTopic(AdminClient admin) throws Exception {
        NewTopic topic = new NewTopic("payments", 12, (short) 3);
        topic.configs(Map.of("min.insync.replicas", "2",
                             "unclean.leader.election.enable", "false"));
        admin.createTopics(Collections.singleton(topic)).all().get();
        System.out.println("Created topic: payments");
    }
}
```

### min.insync.replicas

`min.insync.replicas` (min ISR) defines the minimum number of ISR members that must acknowledge a write when `acks=all`. If the ISR shrinks below this threshold, the broker rejects writes with `NotEnoughReplicasException`.

| RF | min ISR | Tolerates | Trade-off |
|----|---------|-----------|----------|
| 3 | 1 | 2 broker failures, but with data loss risk | Low safety |
| 3 | 2 | 1 broker failure with no data loss | **Recommended** |
| 3 | 3 | 0 broker failures (any failure = unavailability) | Over-cautious |
| 5 | 3 | 2 broker failures with no data loss | High availability |

### Unclean Leader Election

If all ISR members are unavailable (e.g., network partition isolates all in-sync brokers), Kafka faces a choice:
- **Wait for an ISR member to come back** (default with `unclean.leader.election.enable=false`): No data loss but availability is sacrificed.
- **Elect the best out-of-sync follower** (`unclean.leader.election.enable=true`): Restores availability immediately but any messages the old leader acknowledged that haven't replicated to this follower are **permanently lost**.

For financial or transactional systems: always `unclean.leader.election.enable=false`. For high-availability metrics pipelines where some loss is acceptable: `true` may be appropriate.

### Leader Skew

In a healthy cluster, partition leaders should be evenly distributed across brokers. If one broker holds most leaders, it handles disproportionate write and read load. `auto.leader.rebalance.enable=true` (default) triggers periodic rebalancing to restore even leader distribution. Monitor with `kafka.server:type=ReplicaManager,name=LeaderCount`.

### Interview Insight

"What's the difference between replication factor and min.insync.replicas?" — RF determines how many copies exist; min ISR determines how many must actively confirm a write. RF=3 with min ISR=1 gives you fault tolerance for reads (data survives 2 broker failures) but only requires 1 ack for writes — a surviving out-of-sync replica could become leader after a crash and miss recent writes. RF=3 + min ISR=2 + acks=all together form a complete durability guarantee.

## Session 6: Exactly-Once Semantics (EOS)

```mermaid
graph TB
    P[Producer] --> T[Topic]
    T --> P0[Partition 0]
    T --> P1[Partition 1]
    T --> P2[Partition 2]
    P0 --> CG1[Consumer Group 1]
    P1 --> CG1
    P2 --> CG2[Consumer Group 2]
```


Exactly-once semantics (EOS) is one of Kafka's most powerful and most misunderstood features. It is not a single setting — it is the combination of three coordinated mechanisms: idempotent producers, transactional writes, and read-committed consumers. Together they guarantee that each message's effect appears exactly once in the system, even in the presence of producer retries, broker failures, and consumer crashes.

### Why EOS is Hard

Without EOS, you face a dilemma:
- **At-most-once**: commit offset before processing → crash between commit and processing → message skipped.
- **At-least-once**: commit offset after processing → crash between processing and commit → message reprocessed → duplicate effect.

EOS eliminates both failure modes.

### Mechanism 1: Idempotent Producer

Enabled with `enable.idempotence=true`. The broker assigns each producer instance a **Producer ID (PID)**. The producer assigns a **sequence number** to every batch per partition, starting at 0 and incrementing. When a retry arrives, the broker checks: have I already written a batch with this PID + partition + sequence number? If yes, it silently discards the duplicate without returning an error.

This is **within-session idempotence only** — if the producer process restarts, it gets a new PID and sequence numbers reset. Cross-session deduplication requires transactional IDs.

### Mechanism 2: Transactional Producer

A `transactional.id` creates a stable identity for the producer across restarts. The broker fences old producer instances with the same transactional ID by bumping the **producer epoch** — old instances attempting to write are rejected with `ProducerFencedException`.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;
import java.util.*;

public class TransactionalProducer {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, true);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all");
        // Stable identity across restarts — must be unique per producer instance
        props.put(ProducerConfig.TRANSACTIONAL_ID_CONFIG, "payment-processor-1");

        KafkaProducer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props);
        producer.initTransactions(); // registers with the transaction coordinator

        try {
            producer.beginTransaction();

            // Write to multiple partitions/topics atomically
            producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("payments", "txn-001", "{\"amount\":100}"));
            producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("audit-log", "txn-001", "{\"action\":\"debit\"}"));

            // Atomically commit the consumer offset + the produced messages
            // (for consume-transform-produce patterns)
            // producer.sendOffsetsToTransaction(offsets, consumerGroupMetadata);

            producer.commitTransaction();
            System.out.println("Transaction committed successfully");

        } catch (ProducerFencedException e) {
            // Another instance with same transactional.id has started — shut down
            System.err.println("Fenced! Another producer instance is active.");
            producer.close();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            producer.abortTransaction();
            System.err.println("Transaction aborted: " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            producer.close();
        }
    }
}
```

### Mechanism 3: Read-Committed Consumer

Records written inside an open transaction are written to the partition log immediately but are invisible to consumers with `isolation.level=read_committed` until the transaction commits. Aborted transaction records are also skipped. The consumer's effective read position is bounded by the **Last Stable Offset (LSO)** — the offset up to which all transactions are resolved.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer;
import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.*;

public class TransactionalConsumer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "eos-consumer-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringDeserializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
                  StringDeserializer.class.getName());
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, false);
        // Only read committed transactional records
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ISOLATION_LEVEL_CONFIG, "read_committed");

        try (KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props)) {
            consumer.subscribe(Collections.singletonList("payments"));
            while (true) {
                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records =
                    consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(500));
                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    System.out.printf("Committed record: offset=%d value=%s%n",
                        record.offset(), record.value());
                    // All records here are from committed transactions only
                }
                consumer.commitSync();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Consume-Transform-Produce Pattern (EOS End-to-End)

For stream processing that reads from one topic and writes to another, use `sendOffsetsToTransaction()` to atomically commit both the output records and the input consumer offsets in one transaction. If the transaction aborts, both the output and the offset commit are rolled back — the input is reprocessed on restart.

### Kafka Streams EOS

Kafka Streams implements this pattern internally. Set `processing.guarantee=exactly_once_v2` (Kafka 2.5+) and Streams handles producer transactions, offset commits, and consumer isolation automatically.

### Performance Considerations

EOS has overhead: each transaction requires a round-trip to the transaction coordinator for begin, commit, and abort. Throughput drops approximately 20-30% compared to non-transactional producers. Tune `transaction.timeout.ms` (default 60 s) to match your batch processing time — transactions that exceed this timeout are automatically aborted by the broker.

### Interview Insight

"Does exactly-once in Kafka cover external systems?" — No. Kafka EOS is Kafka-internal: it guarantees each record appears exactly once in Kafka topics. If your consumer writes to a database, Kafka EOS does not cover the database write. You still need idempotent database operations (upsert by primary key), distributed transactions (two-phase commit), or the outbox pattern to achieve end-to-end exactly-once across systems.

## Kafka Streams

Kafka Streams is a client library (not a separate cluster) that lets you build real-time stream processing applications on top of Kafka. It reads from input topics, processes data using a directed acyclic graph (DAG) of operations, and writes results back to output topics.

### KStream vs KTable

| Concept | KStream | KTable |
|---------|---------|--------|
| Represents | Unbounded sequence of events | Latest value per key (changelog) |
| Analogy | Append-only log | Database table with upserts |
| Joins | Event-to-event | Point-in-time lookup |
| Use case | Click events, logs | User profiles, inventory counts |

```java
import org.apache.kafka.streams.*;
import org.apache.kafka.streams.kstream.*;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.Serdes;
import java.util.Properties;

public class WordCountApp {

    public static Topology buildTopology() {
        StreamsBuilder builder = new StreamsBuilder();

        // KStream — every message is a distinct event
        KStream<String, String> textLines =
            builder.stream("input-topic", Consumed.with(Serdes.String(), Serdes.String()));

        // Stateless transformation: flatMap + map
        KStream<String, Long> wordCounts = textLines
            .flatMapValues(line -> Arrays.asList(line.toLowerCase().split("\\W+")))
            .groupBy((key, word) -> word)                // repartition by word
            .count(Materialized.as("word-count-store")) // stateful — backed by RocksDB
            .toStream();

        wordCounts.to("output-topic",
            Produced.with(Serdes.String(), Serdes.Long()));

        return builder.build();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(StreamsConfig.APPLICATION_ID_CONFIG, "word-count-app");
        props.put(StreamsConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(StreamsConfig.DEFAULT_KEY_SERDE_CLASS_CONFIG, Serdes.String().getClass());
        props.put(StreamsConfig.DEFAULT_VALUE_SERDE_CLASS_CONFIG, Serdes.String().getClass());

        KafkaStreams streams = new KafkaStreams(buildTopology(), props);
        streams.start();
        Runtime.getRuntime().addShutdownHook(new Thread(streams::close));
    }
}
```

### KTable: Tracking Latest State

```java
// KTable keeps only the latest value per key
KTable<String, String> userProfiles =
    builder.table("user-profiles", Consumed.with(Serdes.String(), Serdes.String()));

// Join a click stream with user profile table
KStream<String, String> clicks =
    builder.stream("user-clicks", Consumed.with(Serdes.String(), Serdes.String()));

KStream<String, String> enriched = clicks.join(
    userProfiles,
    (clickData, profile) -> clickData + " | user=" + profile
);
enriched.to("enriched-clicks");
```

### Windowing

Windows group events by time for aggregations:

- **Tumbling** — fixed, non-overlapping windows (every 1 min)
- **Hopping** — fixed size, overlapping (1 min window, advance 30 sec)
- **Session** — gap-based, groups activity bursts

```java
KTable<Windowed<String>, Long> windowedCounts = textLines
    .flatMapValues(line -> Arrays.asList(line.split(" ")))
    .groupBy((key, word) -> word)
    .windowedBy(TimeWindows.ofSizeWithNoGrace(Duration.ofMinutes(1)))
    .count();
```

### Interview Tips
- KStream joins require co-partitioning (same number of partitions, same key).
- Kafka Streams uses changelog topics and RocksDB for fault-tolerant state.
- `APPLICATION_ID_CONFIG` acts as the consumer group ID and is used for changelog topic naming.
- Prefer `suppress()` to emit only final windowed results rather than every update.

