    "poll.interval.ms": "1000"
  }
}
```

Deploy via REST API: `POST http://connect:8083/connectors`

### Schema Registry & Avro

Schema Registry stores versioned schemas. Producers encode messages using the schema ID; consumers decode using the same registry — ensuring compatibility without embedding the schema in every message.

```java
import io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroSerializer;
import io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroDeserializer;
import org.apache.avro.generic.GenericRecord;
import org.apache.avro.generic.GenericData;
import org.apache.avro.Schema;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import java.util.Properties;

public class AvroProducerExample {

    private static final String SCHEMA_STR = "{"
        + "\"type\": \"record\","
        + "\"name\": \"Order\","
        + "\"fields\": ["
        + "  {\"name\": \"orderId\", \"type\": \"string\"},"
        + "  {\"name\": \"amount\",  \"type\": \"double\"},"
        + "  {\"name\": \"status\",  \"type\": \"string\"}"
        + "]}"
    ;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            KafkaAvroSerializer.class.getName());
        props.put("schema.registry.url", "http://localhost:8081");

        Schema schema = new Schema.Parser().parse(SCHEMA_STR);
        try (KafkaProducer<String, GenericRecord> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props)) {
            GenericRecord order = new GenericData.Record(schema);
            order.put("orderId", "ORD-001");
            order.put("amount", 99.95);
            order.put("status", "PENDING");

            ProducerRecord<String, GenericRecord> record =
                new ProducerRecord<>("orders", "ORD-001", order);
            producer.send(record, (meta, ex) -> {
                if (ex != null) ex.printStackTrace();
                else System.out.printf("Sent to %s partition %d%n",
                    meta.topic(), meta.partition());
            });
        }
    }
}
```

### Schema Evolution & Compatibility

| Strategy | Rule | Use When |
|----------|------|----------|
| BACKWARD | New schema reads old data | Adding optional fields |
| FORWARD | Old schema reads new data | Removing optional fields |
| FULL | Both directions | Rolling upgrades |
| NONE | No checks | Development only |

**Safe changes**: Add optional fields with defaults, rename via aliases.
**Breaking changes**: Remove required fields, change field types — these fail registry validation.

### Single Message Transforms (SMTs)

SMTs modify records in-flight inside Connect without custom code:

```json
"transforms": "addTimestamp,maskPII",
"transforms.addTimestamp.type": "org.apache.kafka.connect.transforms.InsertField$Value",
"transforms.addTimestamp.timestamp.field": "ingest_time",
"transforms.maskPII.type": "org.apache.kafka.connect.transforms.MaskField$Value",
"transforms.maskPII.fields": "email,ssn"
```

### Interview Tips
- Debezium is the most common source connector — it uses CDC (Change Data Capture) to stream DB changes via the binlog/WAL.
- Schema Registry uses a binary wire format: 1 magic byte + 4-byte schema ID + Avro payload.
- BACKWARD compatibility is the Confluent default and the safest for most teams.

## Kafka Performance Tuning

```mermaid
graph TB
    P[Producer] --> T[Topic]
    T --> P0[Partition 0]
    T --> P1[Partition 1]
    T --> P2[Partition 2]
    P0 --> CG1[Consumer Group 1]
    P1 --> CG1
    P2 --> CG2[Consumer Group 2]
```


Kafka's default configuration optimizes for safety, not throughput. Production systems often need explicit tuning across three dimensions: throughput, latency, and resource utilization.

### Producer Tuning

The three most impactful producer knobs:

| Config | Default | Throughput Focus | Latency Focus |
|--------|---------|------------------|--------------|
| `batch.size` | 16 KB | 256 KB – 1 MB | 1–16 KB |
| `linger.ms` | 0 ms | 5–100 ms | 0 ms |
| `compression.type` | none | lz4 or snappy | none |
| `buffer.memory` | 32 MB | 64–256 MB | 32 MB |
| `acks` | 1 | 0 or 1 | all (for safety) |

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.*;
import java.util.Properties;

public class HighThroughputProducer {

    public static Properties highThroughputConfig() {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.ByteArraySerializer");

        // Batching: accumulate up to 512 KB or wait 20 ms, whichever comes first
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BATCH_SIZE_CONFIG, 512 * 1024);  // 512 KB
        props.put(ProducerConfig.LINGER_MS_CONFIG, 20);           // 20 ms wait

        // Compression reduces network I/O — lz4 is best throughput/CPU tradeoff
        props.put(ProducerConfig.COMPRESSION_TYPE_CONFIG, "lz4");

        // Larger buffer so the producer is never blocked waiting for batches to drain
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BUFFER_MEMORY_CONFIG, 128L * 1024 * 1024); // 128 MB

        // Allow up to 5 in-flight requests per connection for throughput
        props.put(ProducerConfig.MAX_IN_FLIGHT_REQUESTS_PER_CONNECTION, 5);

        // Fire-and-forget style acks for maximum throughput (at-most-once)
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "1");

        return props;
    }

    public static Properties lowLatencyConfig() {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");

        // No waiting — send immediately
        props.put(ProducerConfig.LINGER_MS_CONFIG, 0);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BATCH_SIZE_CONFIG, 1);   // effectively no batching
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "1");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.COMPRESSION_TYPE_CONFIG, "none");

        return props;
    }
}
```

### Consumer Tuning

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.*;
import java.util.Properties;

public class HighThroughputConsumer {

    public static Properties config() {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "perf-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,
            "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.ByteArrayDeserializer");

        // Fetch up to 50 MB per poll — reduces poll() call overhead
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.FETCH_MAX_BYTES_CONFIG, 50 * 1024 * 1024);
        // Minimum bytes to wait for before returning — avoids tiny fetches
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.FETCH_MIN_BYTES_CONFIG, 1024 * 1024); // 1 MB
        // Max wait if min bytes not met
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.FETCH_MAX_WAIT_MS_CONFIG, 500);
        // Max records per poll() — tune based on processing time
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.MAX_POLL_RECORDS_CONFIG, 1000);

        return props;
    }
}
```

### Compression Comparison

| Codec | CPU Cost | Compression Ratio | Best For |
|-------|----------|-------------------|----------|
| none | Zero | 1x | Already compressed data |
| gzip | High | Best (~5x) | Archival, cold paths |
| snappy | Low | Good (~2.5x) | General use |
| lz4 | Lowest | Good (~2.5x) | High-throughput hot paths |
| zstd | Medium | Best modern (~4x) | Balanced throughput+ratio |

### OS-Level Tuning

- Set `vm.swappiness=1` — Kafka relies heavily on page cache; swapping kills throughput.
- Increase `ulimit -n 100000` — Kafka opens many file descriptors.
- Use XFS or ext4 with `noatime` mount option.
- Allocate dedicated disks; avoid NAS/SAN for log directories.

### Interview Tips
- `linger.ms` and `batch.size` work together — a batch sends when either limit is reached.
- Enabling idempotence (`enable.idempotence=true`) forces `acks=all` and `max.in.flight=5`, which slightly reduces throughput but guarantees exactly-once delivery.
- Monitor `producer-metrics` (batch-size-avg, record-send-rate) and `consumer-fetch-manager-metrics` (bytes-consumed-rate, records-lag).

